}
2. Flink Job Configuration : Spring’s dependency injection makes it easy to configure Flink:

@Configuration

public class FlinkConfig {

 @Bean

 public StreamExecutionEnvironment streamExecutionEnvironment() {

 StreamExecutionEnvironment env = StreamExecutionEnvironment.getExecutionEnvironment();

 env.setRestartStrategy(RestartStrategies.fixedDelayRestart(3, 10000));

 env.enableCheckpointing(60000);

 return env;

 }



 @Bean

 public ParameterTool flinkParameters() {

 Map<String, String> parameters = new HashMap<>();

 parameters.put("bootstrap.servers", bootstrapServers);

 parameters.put("group.id", consumerGroupId);

 parameters.put("input-topic", inputTopic);

 parameters.put("output-topic", outputTopic);

 return ParameterTool.fromMap(parameters);

 }

}
3. Stream Processing Pipeline: The core of the application is the Flink processing pipeline

@Component

public class EventProcessingJob {

 @EventListener(ApplicationReadyEvent.class)

 public void startJob() {

 try {

 // Create Kafka source and sink

 FlinkKafkaConsumer<Event> kafkaSource = new FlinkKafkaConsumer<>(

 parameters.get("input-topic"),

 new EventDeserializationSchema(),

 consumerProps

 );



 FlinkKafkaProducer<AggregatedResult> kafkaSink = new FlinkKafkaProducer<>(

 parameters.get("output-topic"),

 new EventSerializationSchema(),

 consumerProps

 );

 // Build the processing pipeline

 DataStream<Event> inputStream = env.addSource(kafkaSource);



 DataStream<Event> validEvents = inputStream

 .filter(new ValidEventFilter());



 DataStream<Event> enrichedEvents = validEvents

 .map(new EventEnricher());



 DataStream<Event> processedEvents = enrichedEvents

 .keyBy(event -> event.getType())

 .process(new StatefulEventProcessor());



 DataStream<AggregatedResult> aggregatedResults = processedEvents

 .keyBy(event -> event.getType())

 .window(TumblingProcessingTimeWindows.of(Time.minutes(5)))

 .aggregate(new EventAggregator(), new EventWindowProcessor());



 // Send results to Kafka

 aggregatedResults.addSink(kafkaSink);



 // Execute the job

 env.execute("Event Processing Microservice");

 } catch (Exception e) {

 logger.error("Error starting Flink job", e);

 }

 }

}
4. Stateful Processing : One of Flink’s key features is stateful processing, which allows tracking information across events

public static class StatefulEventProcessor extends KeyedProcessFunction<String, Event, Event> {

 private ValueState<Double> lastValueState;



 @Override

 public void open(Configuration parameters) {

 ValueStateDescriptor<Double> descriptor = new ValueStateDescriptor<>(

 "last-value", Double.class);

 lastValueState = getRuntimeContext().getState(descriptor);

 }



 @Override

 public void processElement(Event event, Context ctx, Collector<Event> out) throws Exception {

 Double lastValue = lastValueState.value();

 lastValueState.update(event.getValue());



 // Detect significant changes

 if (lastValue != null) {

 double change = Math.abs((event.getValue() - lastValue) / lastValue) * 100;

 if (change > 10.0) {

 event.setPayload(event.getPayload() + " (significant change: " + change + "%)");

 }

 }



 out.collect(event);

 }

}
5. Windowed Aggregation : For analytics over time periods, Flink provides windowing capabilities

// Aggregate events in 5-minute windows

DataStream<AggregatedResult> aggregatedResults = processedEvents

 .keyBy(event -> event.getType())

 .window(TumblingProcessingTimeWindows.of(Time.minutes(5)))

 .aggregate(new EventAggregator(), new EventWindowProcessor());
6. REST API : Spring Boot provides a REST interface to interact with the system:

@RestController

@RequestMapping("/api/jobs")

public class JobController {

 private final KafkaTemplate<String, Event> kafkaTemplate;



 @PostMapping("/events")

 public ResponseEntity<String> publishEvent(@RequestBody Event event) {

 if (event.getId() == null) {

 event.setId(UUID.randomUUID().toString());

 }



 kafkaTemplate.send(inputTopic, event.getId(), event);

 return ResponseEntity.ok("Event published: " + event.getId());

 }



 @GetMapping("/status")

 public ResponseEntity<Map<String, String>> getJobsStatus() throws Exception {

 // Implementation to get Flink job status

 }

}
Conclusion :
------------

Both **Apache Flink** and **Kafka Streams** are powerful tools in the stream-processing space, but they cater to different needs and use cases. **Kafka Streams** is a great choice for simple, Kafka-centric stream processing tasks, whereas **Apache Flink** is a more advanced framework that excels in large-scale, complex event-driven architectures and real-time analytics.

When choosing between the two, it’s important to assess the complexity of your processing needs, the scalability required, and how tightly integrated you want the system to be with Kafka. If you’re just looking for lightweight stream processing within the Kafka ecosystem, Kafka Streams will likely suffice. If your application demands more sophisticated processing, stateful computations, or real-time analytics, Apache Flink might be the better option.

Ultimately, both are excellent tools, and your decision will depend on your specific architecture and requirements.

Combining Apache Flink with Spring Boot creates a powerful platform for building stateful, scalable microservices. This architecture provides:

*   Real-time data processing with low latency
*   Stateful operations for complex event processing
*   Easy integration with external systems via Kafka
*   Scalable and fault-tolerant processing

The key to success is properly addressing serialization, state management, and lifecycle issues while following best practices for both Flink and Spring Boot. For the complete source code and implementation details, you can refer to our GitHub repository ([https://github.com/vontamar/flink-microservice.git](https://github.com/vontamar/flink-microservice.git))

